reviews.review: The movie desperately tries to thrive on our good memories from the original thrilogy, while failing at making an original story that would bring emotions as well. The main story elements feel forced and without logic, I felt uneasy watching certain scenes (with Leia), and the elements that work well are mainly parts of the original thrilogy. I don't feel like watching the movie again. However, it managed to want me to watch the original thrilogy again.

Satisfying ending for me to an uneven saga. The movie wrapped in a satisfying ending overcoming a but if a jumpy scattershot beginning few minutes. I think the necessary final goodbyes were given for the pertinent characters.

I thought it was easily the best movie of this trilogy. It was fast paced and enjoyed the ride. I do feel that Disney did not have a clear path as to which way they wanted this trilogy to go. JJ Abrams did a good job of fixing things Rian Johnson may have messed up in The Last Jedi.
Absolute waste of time and the final nail in the Disney Star Wars failures

Gorgeous movie! A glorious ending for the most important saga of our lives. "The Rise of Skywalker" is a wonderful show, a film that brings me back to my child days, with all that illusion and emotions. Adam Driver keeps proving that he's one of the greatest actors of this century. Long live to Star Wars! Long live to Skywalker!
rushed ending with very similar plot points as episode VI
What a disappointing end for the Skywalker family. #BenSoloDeservedBetter

Seems like a frantic race to tie up loose threads in the most convoluted way possible, while actively disregarding any meaningful sacrifices and arcs of previous trilogies, yet continuously dragging characters back from the dead.
The first 2 acts feel like you're watching a video game unfold.

This film will disappoint those who wanted a fitting end to 40+ years of story telling, as well as those that are discovering Star Wars in the cinema through the final trilogy.

Storylines rehash episodes 4-6 as homage that just breeds predictability.  Romantic scenes outdo Ep 2, and attracted more laughs and groans than developing the charatcter of Rey.

The first hour is a blur of jump cuts and tangential hops, that at least did not fall through the modern trap of splitting the story into two parts.
